s 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>sandes</i> ‘sands’, for someone who lived at or near a sandy place, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Sands in Carlisle (Cumberland) or Sands Cottages in West Hoathly (Sussex). See   Sand  , of which <i>Sands</i> may sometimes be a plural form or a variant, with excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare also   Sandes   and   Sandys  .","History: Comfort Sands, a revolutionary patriot born in 1748 at what is now Sands’ Point, Long Island, NY, was descended from James Sand(y)s (1622–95), who emigrated from Reading, Berkshire, England, to Plymouth, MA, and followed Anne Hutchinson to Westchester County, NY, and subsequently RI. In 1661 he settled on Block Island, RI."],"variants":[{"name":"Sandys","meanings":["English: variant of   Sands  ."]},{"name":"Sand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Bertel, Ejnar, Lars, Levinus, Nels, Niels, Thor.","English, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name for someone who lived on or near a patch of sandy soil, from the vocabulary word <i>sand</i> (German <i>Sand</i>). As a Swedish name it was often purely ornamental, and as a Jewish artificial. It is also found in France (see 3 below).","English: habitational name from a place such as Send (Surrey) or Sound (Cheshire), named with Middle English <i>sand</i>, <i>sond</i> ‘sand’."]},{"name":"Sandes","meanings":["English: variant of   Sands  .","Galician: habitational name from any of various places so named in Galicia (Spain). Compare   Sandez  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":67,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":76,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":87,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"John Sands was born in 1482, in England. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1482–":"1482–Surnud","1502–1544":"1502–1544","1482–Male":"1482–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1544":"1544","1482":"1482","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fi":{"1482–":"1482–Kuollut","1502–1544":"1502–1544","1482–Male":"1482–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1544":"1544","1482":"1482","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fr":{"1482–":"1482–Décédé","1502–1544":"1502–1544","1482–Male":"1482–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1544":"1544","1482":"1482","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"John Sands est né en 1482, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1482–":"1482–Verstorben","1502–1544":"1502–1544","1482–Male":"1482–Verstorben","1569":"1569","155